Not only is the evidence stronger before undergoing a Phase III trial but also the risk and reward is completely different than a germline edit.

But ... this is deeply unethical on humans. It implies doing experiments you know are not going to work some proportion of the time on naive embryos where your default position is that this embryo would be healthy

This is ok for experimental plants and animals - make the change, grow up to adulthood - is fine, and a 50% yield of results in line with prediction would be a great thing - many plant programs do this (often with introgression not CRISPR)

(there is a whole separate question whether robust prediction is clinically useful. I will park this divergent thread for a moment!). But statistical prediction of an individual is *not* the same as predicting the result of an experiment >>

Even so, given careful set up of the problem (proper prediction), making sure we're not stacking the deck (so we have to use all the other easy to get predictors, eg, age, sex) and enough diverse samples we should be able to get to "robust prediction"

But for prediction it means we've got another extenistential modelling issue - we *know* even a "random British person" is not the same as a "random person from UK BioBank" (let alone a random French person, or US or a random Kenyan). Notice --- this is not genetics necessarily

There is another subtle gotcha between discovery and prediction - they are quite different tasks, and how one sets up samples, and manipulates data on the way in is different. Eg, for discovery, the fact that UK BioBank is about twice as healthy on average is annoying, but ok
Personally I think we've got to bite the bullet if we are going to do prediction - and get enough samples from enough diverse people to nail everything (ideally; fine map all major causal loci).

As LD is sensitive to recombination points (broadly similar in humans worldwide) and population expansion and population history (by definition *not* similar as we move between humans) this is a real headache.

This is a good trick - it works really well for farm animals and plants - but it makes our prediction model more fragile. When we use it with humans we've got another "model" question to ask - is this model valid for my unseen person I want to predict?

The alternative is exploit this structure, allowing one to estimate the overall prediction of an individual better than having to know each beta correctly. (Confusingly though we often call the relevant prediction variables beta. We shouldn't as it confuses people, but we do)

(BTW - this is going to go on for *years* more. Not this precisely, but the nature of the UK's relationship to the EU. Boy is it going to be exhausting and plays to a real tired, old view of UK for many British voters that I just think we should leave behind).
But Hindsight is such a wonderful gift. Living in the here and now, assumming May's WA fails again (it's actually not so mad) then a more forced choice pan-Parliament voting is needed (and quick).

We (ie, UK) should obviously had done this process or something a bit more managed (!!) ideally two years ago, (plus wise triggering of A50) and certainly sometime post the 2017 election when it was clear that we had a hung Parliament during s serious constitutional change choice

(To be fair to politicians, actually alot of politics is like this it is just that we don't see it aired so much, and the current parties are not aligned *internally* on the Brexit quesition(s) making the mechanics of this all super-tricky. Still - better leaders needed!)

So - there is a shape of how things could progress from the UK side and frankly it is now internal Tory party politics (as ever) and then UK party politics now driving the agenda not (sadly) national interest. Unedifying.

The other broad view is confirmatory referendum has strong support (most votes, but less abstentions, so bigger margin to overcome). I think this is a good idea to make sure the country has looked the options squarely ahead of them and done it together (whichever way).
The customs union (proposed by Tory legend and rare Tory Europhile Ken Clarke) is oddly consistent as one of the outcomes in the broad political declaration of May's Deal.

I know the UK Parliament and Government look as shambolic as the last 12 months, but the indicative votes did show that Customs Union approach has the largest support, nearly a majority with many abstentions (SNP - looking at you!)

Moral of the story - scientists find the word "epigenetics" complex. Your baseline is that you should be very skeptical about human trans generational epigenetics (its not formally impossible; it is though super unlikely).

The Dutch famine, Holocaust survivors and other stories have more straightforward and clear cut explanations via both change in behaviour in parents (most simple) or these 1 or 2 generational exposure aspects.

This "parent of origin" imprinting is executed via epigenetics (in the "DNA modification" sense) and both this and the oocyte aspect means 1 or 2 generational information transfer happens all the time. But not as far as we know, multi-generational (except Agouti).

This parent-of-origin reprogramming has some striking and usually lethal effects when it goes wrong and some specific subtle effects on some phenotypes (the most famous being certain types of baldness which come only from the mother's line due to this).

Second, nearly all our genomes go through "epigenetic reprogramming" in the germline (meaning - removing all DNA modification and then adding special "you are sperm or egg" modifications) with the extra twist that at some places the eggs are programmed one way, sperm another

The oocyte (unfertilized egg) that made you had a key cell division whilst it was in your grandmother, in the developing body of your mother. There is a little bit of you that existed way back then (in my case... 1944). Weird, but true.

Some caveats here. Mammals have two well known properties. The first is that the female germline is laid down in the developing foetus and kept in stasis until the menstrual cycle. This means there is a direct cellular connection from every mammal to their maternal grandmother

Anne Fergusson-Smith, head of genetics in Cambridge, one of the world's leading epigeneticists and an absolutely no nonsense glaswegian has looked super carefully for more loci like this in Mouse. Not found one more *trans generational*. https://t.co/TybV7e4ZUw
If you want to know, multi-generational transgenerational epigenetics is rare (but observable) in plants. It is very rare in mammals, with only one good locus (Agouti coat colour) that is

So - you don't need a fancy science term to say you are more than your DNA - you are - (and this is from a geneticist) - and you don't need a fancy science term to describe the impact of behaviour in families being passed down. We call that "behaviours" or "family behaviours"

DNA is *not* your destiny (as I've often stressed) - it is just often really useful - firstly for research and steadily coming into healthcare, but ... it doesn't mean you shouldn't exercise, choose what you eat, be happy, do what you want.

First off, the popular understanding of genetics has a big overreach (and there is a whole possible thread that geneticists don't help this in our enthusiasm for our science); geneticists are completely comfortable with non-genetic stuff happening
The @BBCFuture one was on this topic of "inherieted trauma" via epigenetics (it is so misguided...)

Pretty much uniformly though the use of "epigenetics" in the broader, non science, world is associated with an often vague "there is more to life than DNA as a fixed destiny", often linked to transgenerational inheritance, or environmental impact

Even well established scientists often have to stop each other and ask "what do you really mean by epigenetics here" and loop back to confirm which of the above definitions the other scientist is using. Yup, it's exhausting.
(there is one final definition - everything which is not genetic, which is a really weird definition as it is pretty much all of biology).

It might mean cell state as cellular memory. It might mean "some funky inheritance pattern from parents to child or complex, non standard genetic behaviour." and it might mean "Non DNA based inheritance".

CRAM has a very active community of developers, based around the Large Scale Genomics workstream of @GA4GH led by @drtkeane and Oliver Hofmann and they are tackling future things ike base modification representation.

CRAM's most obvious benefit is reduced space (30% to 50% of the corresponding BAM, depending on details) but there are many other benefits - absolutely precise definition of the aligned reference (playing well with @GA4GH's refget service) and crazy long read support

CRAM is really mature now. It is a swap in replacement for BAM for htslib (C) and htsjdk (Java) - meaning GATK, BioPerl and BioPython, Ensembl, ENA, ANVIL, TopMed and many other software stacks already use it routinely, day to day, now

As a researcher who helped at the start of CRAM I am so impressed in its maturity, mainly due to the work of @sangerinstitute @emblebi and @broadinstitute's software engineers - a particular person to highlight is @BonfieldJames who has always pushed for the community standard
The next two weeks will see a sustained push from @GA4GH to get more people to adopt CRAM into their research and healthcare pipelines. https://t.co/Pus3892yrB

I am no politician nor political pro. I am however from a pretty "traditional" UK background but have fully internalised European ways. I can easily - and constructively I hope - critique but more importantly, realise this is an argument in a broad family of European nations

But - whilst trying to stay away from being condenscending (I've been there - it is not a good look) - the fact that we are families, and there are many, younger, people that *are* comfortable with these changes, can navigate the cultural aspects of being an EU member is useful

Finally, I think we underplayed the inter-generational reassurance possible for older leave. It would be interesting to know how well that worked for Ireland's abortion debate from people in Ireland (and stats - to what extent did this help)

We also don't make enough of the independent armed forces, security and health delivery (health is protected as a nation state competency) which is true now inside the EU, and will only deepen inside of the Euro. These also play well to the Britain first leave audience
Of course there are risks in this - and complex trade offs - but there is a strong intellectual argument that the right place to make this is precisely in the "in the EU out of the Eurozone" status.

This is key. For intellectual leave, us not being part of the Euro speaks to Macron's inner and outer circles, and places us in the outer circle. The big questions of a European super-state will be argued over for the Eurozone countries
(For that you can thank not just John Major and his struggles to keep the Tory party together but also Gordon Brown in the Blair years. Strange bed fellows)

Going to the message is important (and important to be tested) but I personally don't think people have played the card that the UK "played a blinder" (in Britian first leave language) in the 20 years before this, in particular not being part of the Eurozone

But this trust is broader and more cultural than just "did you believe in leave previously". Oliver Letwin for intellecutal leave; Ken Clarke for older leave; Gary Lineker, Jurgen Klopp for Britian first leave for example.

So - what to do? The first thing is realise that the messenger as well as the message is important - people have to trust the other person. This is why ex-Leave people are powerful in this, and someone like me (for all my attempts at empathy) is not.

This last group is a broad range of ages, and mainly away from cities. They work hard, often for not much money, go on holiday to Europe but don't want to be part of Europe. Boris and Jacob Rees Mogg are ok to them because they to have obvious pride in the UK.

(I note for example when I say I am proud Brit and a committed European, the complaints I get is exclusively for the first statement - a proud Brit - for some people in Remain this is impossible to reconcile)

They don't understand why we didn't leave straight after the referendum, and dont mind that leaving might make us collectively poorer. They are proud of the UK and really dislike the sense that being proud of the UK is considered wrong

The third: "Britain first Leave". These are the people who just want out - they get they have to rub along with the rest of the people in the UK, but see no reason to have to understand any other country, let alone the EU

They are naturally older (though not all old in fact), often retired and although they get that they have to think about the people in work, they point out that they did fine (again, hold off the rebuttals for a moment!)

They put the EU and its complications, different rules, alongside all sorts of things - from the internet through to political correctness - into not only things they don't understand, but also things that "damage Britain". They want to save Britain from this world.

The second: "older Leave". These are people who are connected to the pre-Common Market UK - either directly remember it or have that cultural connection to this earlier world. They want a distinctive British culture and combine that with a dislike of the "changes" to UK
These often are Adam Smith style free markets people, educated, reasonably well off.

They point out there are plenty of countries with less GDP and people who interact perfectly well worldwide without a super-national structure, and think that whatever the merits of a federal Europe (or ever closer union) *culturally* it wont ultimately work *practically*

The first: "intellectual Leave". They intensely dislike the hodge-podge of governance around the EU, and even with Spitzenkandidaten think the democratic deficit of the EU is plain dangerous. The eurozone is destined for collapse as it is nowhere close to an optimal currency area
"It's like in academia, everything is a big f$#Kng deal because the stakes are so small." Wendy Rhoades, Season 2 of Billlions. Also known as Sayre's Law. And well worth remembering.

Notice how it clearly peaks in west Africa and...arctic Europe?Does this look at all like evidence for discrete races?? [8/n] https://t.co/Kl4JRY7dfK

Defining resistance and tolerance. Resistance is high MIC after 24hr growth. Halo size determines susceptible vs resistant. Is concentration dependent. Citing work from @AnnaSelmecki on aneuploidy driving resistance.  #fungal19

Lots more work in this space on its way - more genomics, genomes, crosses, known and novel genes for a number of different drug classes.

3. cont. Importantly, we show how a fragmented genome assembly may have resulted in a very different conclusion, and that high-quality genomes are important for this work. It really is a nice example of justifying continued genome improvement for more precise biological insight.

3. understanding the genome-wide context is important - not for all cases - but certainly for traits like drug resistance. We do this by using the new chromosome-scale genome assembly from @parasitegenomes and @BUGConsortium .  More on the genome itself in the next few months.

2. cont. We exclude almost all previous candidate genes linked to ivermectin resistance here, and some genome mining suggests that the resistance mechanism is likely to be novel. Again, the problem with candidates is the can't really tell you about anything novel.

2. Genetic crosses provide a very powerful way to account for these genetic differences. Again, no surprises, but has been used only a few times in this context in helminths. We reduce this genome-wide "noise" to a single region on ChrV linked to resistance.

1. Helminths like H. contortus are genetically diverse! No surprise - the THM is direct comparison between isolates to find drug resistance genes is going to be misled by population structure, esp. if looking at single candidate genes. We show genome-wide that this is the case.

So why don't we use number of FP instead of precision? Describe a somatic variant caller as detecting 90% of somatic variants, and producing 10 false positives per genome on average. Should go for most cancer types.What are people's thoughts on this? Am I missing something?3/3

There is no reason why FP would scale with TP. FPs are typically induced by different kinds of noise, independently of any actual somatic variants present in the sample. Precision will be much higher in a melanoma than in an AML for example, due to higher mutation rate.2/3

When benchmarking somatic variant callers, people typically useprecision = TP/(TP+FP)recall = TP/(TP+FN)TP typically scales with FN, so recall measures something that will be decently constant across samples. With exceptions of course. Precision though...1/3

Inherently more expensive than small molecules. At this point I can't think of a way to make cellular therapies like Car-T cheap. You are taking cells out of someone, engineering them, growing them, sending them back and infusing them into the patient. 6/

But I think we can solve that given time. The long term issue is cost. These new therapies cost a ton. Yes, yes, biopharma charges too much, sure, maybe. But cellular therapy is inherently more expensive than, say, antibody drugs which themselves are 5/

There's a catch to the excitement. Two catches actually, one short and one long term. The short term is, even the miracle stuff coming out if biopharma isn't curing everyone in a given target indication. We don't know why. This is frustrating. 4/
And, it's an amazing time in biopharma! Cellular therapies of various sorts, Gene editing, CRISPR, #genomics--holy cow are there exciting things going on! BUT...3/

Then I started thinking about the mind of a sea cucumber. Their nervous system is much the same, but the nerves run along the length of the body.I'm still pondering on what this means for their experience.
If you surgically severed the nerve-ring of a more typical starfish, I suspect it would also tear itself into pieces.I've looked for, but haven't found, a paper describing such an experiment.

Those little aquarium Asterina could live the life they do because they have a dysfunctional nerve-ring. As soon as an arm or group of arms get strong enough to tear themselves free of the others... they fragment.
They have a ring of nerves circling their mouth, connecting the nervous system of each arm. Kind of like how our corpus callosum keeps us integrated into a single mind (usually).
A way this could work is if each arm contains essentially it's own mind, but they usually keep their direction of movement synchronized.

The observation that led me to this was watching a small starfish in a saltwater aquarium tearing itself apart. The arms on one side decided to go a different direction than the arms on the other.It was an "Asterina". Common in aquaria, but no scientific name last I checked.

You could in theory fit the pairs of (RNA velocity, RNA abundance) to a master equation and you're done! That would be really awesome and surely someone has tried that. I can think of, however, three caveats to this fit:
Using this framework, the holy grail of gene network analysis in general then is a (chemical) master equation, where the transition matrix describes the true, microscale network of the system.

When you actually have temporal information, you can attempt to model the true dynamics directly. If you don't have enough samples, this is challenging for all but the simplest of processes (e.g. cell cycle).

or actual temporal information. When you do the former, increase samples in intermediates, and try to mine trends,you end up with the so-called 'pseudotime' analyses, which you can use to group genes. In this setting, network analysis means extracting course-grained gene dynamics

In this case, your gene modules will correspond with coordinated genes that are markers of various cell populations. That is, you are finding marker gene programs in this setting. This resolution is increased by either more samples that capture more intermediates,

In single-cell contexts, I like to think of "gene-network analysis" in terms of temporal resolution. In on extreme, e,g. no temporal resolution and your sample is a blob of single cells, gene-network analysis means analyzing the covariance of genes in a single,static distribution

The nifty thing from the plant breeding perspective, is that these new seedling clones will likely produce viable seed of their own. This means I can breed for more varieties with this neat side-crawling trait over the next several years.

I expect to have enough bulbs from the clone to make a meal of them at the end of this next season. It will be edible, but I don't know if it will be sweet or pungent. The seedlings so far have hinted at a range of flavors (from their different scents).

That they didn't grow super crowded means they will probably have less of a problem with various diseases that can arise when onions are grown tightly packed together.Between this and the improved aesthetics of the resulting bulbs, I'm really happy with the seedling.

Now, these bulbs didn't travel as much as a wild plant might want to. (The final bulbs only had about an inch between them.) They'll politely remain in the general area that I planted them for many years.

The 3rd plant did something a bit more creative. The new bulb divisions crawled away from each other using those nifty contractile roots I mentioned. As a result, each bulb was perfectly round. Over years, this clone might spread into a large patch. Most would be crowded and die.

It takes a few years to go from seed to enough of a clone to make a meal. Of the 3 selected clones that remained from my first seedling batch (some didn't bulb, others didn't survive our winter), 2 formed nests. The bulbs grew with flat sides from being stuck to each other.

A #PlantBreeding project I've been working on for several years is to breed up new varieties of perennial onions (called "potato onions" or "multiplier onions"). In most clones the bulbs divide & remain attached to each other, forming a "nest" that can be broken apart to replant.

Some wild bulbs use the same contractile roots to pull themselves sideways, to spread divisions away from each other. This behavior has largely been bred out of domesticated/garden varieties, since we would generally rather our garden plants stay where we put them.

If you plant a flower bulb too shallow in the garden, over a few years it will migrate to a depth it likes better. They do this using specialized roots called "contractile roots". They grow out into the soil & then contract, pulling the bulb deeper.https://t.co/QyCigsXu9X

For most plants, their only significant travel is when they're seeds. Those that grow as rhizomes or bulbs can also travel by simply growing to a new place. It takes time, but is effective over the many years the plants can live.

We tend to think of plants as immobile things that animals eat and interact with. However, every plant has to have a way to travel. Without such an ability, a species would never spread into new territory and would likely go extinct during the next local disaster.

Problem is though that you can't do this directly in tensorflow because you end up with lots of timesteps and scaling is with T^2. But... in certain cases (not sure I followed this) it is better, results in same asymptotic complexity as MD.

Basic langevin dynamics, can also be written in tensorflow. So... once you've done that, could you directly compute a gradient of a loss, where loss defined by difference between what MD engine predicts and what we observed?

Tensorflow has automatic differentiation for computing gradients with respect to all kinds of things in the system, e.g. parameters, etc. With autodiff you only need to implement the energy function and you get forces, Hessians, mixed partials, etc. "for free" with a single call.
Can we improve the parameters we already have using a modern ML engine? Or, thought experiment, what about just rewrite an MD engine in Tensorflow?

5) Future work will focus on what host/microbe factors are responsible for tipping entire communities from susceptible to resistant phenotypes so that we might harness this phenomenon to protect our gut microbiota from exposure to therapeutic antibiotic treatment regimes.

4) RNAseq data indicates that non-responder phenotypes appear to combat antibiotic assault through a combination of efflux transporter upregulation and a reduced growth rate across the entire gut community.

3) Despite minimal differences between non-responders and untreated controls in 16S community structure, RNAseq showed that 27% of bacterial transcripts were deferentially expressed between antibiotic non-responder mice (during treatment) and untreated control mice.

2) Microbiomes that respond to antibiotics (antibiotic-susceptible) show transient collapse of community structure and biomass, and permanent loss of ASV diversity. Non-responder (resistant) microbiomes are protected from these effects.

1) Antibiotic treatment duration and seaweed diet (seaweed contains antimicrobial plant secondary compounds that we hypothesized might prime resistance) had no detectable impact on the frequency of the non-responder (resistant) phenotype.
